x4freetext: Pb207(n,2n gamma) cross sections used for correction.
Accelerator GELINA. 1 ns pulses, mean energy 100 MeV,
repetition rate 800 Hz, average current ~ 7 microA.
Neutron produced via U-238(g,xn) and U-238(g,f)
The neutron beam was collimated to a diameter 61 mm.
characterized by isotope mass spectrometry at IRMM.
Mass 43.2781 g, diameter 50.0 mm, thickness 2.02 mm ,
Sample was placed at 198.551 m from the neutron source.
Exp.I: large radiogenic 206Pb sample and a fast
Exp.II: highly enriched, smaller 206Pb sample and
Time-of-flight bins of 9.5 ns for Exp I and 8 ns
for Exp II were used resulting in a resolution of
1.3 keV at 1 MeV and 42 keV at 10 MeV for Exp I
(1.1 and 35 keV, respectively, for Exp II).
Four detectors were used with relative efficiencies
from 95% to 100% in Exp.I, from 76% to 105% in EXP.II.
Two detectors were placed at 110 deg and two at 150deg.
The distance the sample - the front of the detectors
The photopeak efficiency of the HPGe detectors was
measured using pointlike sources placed in the sample
For neutron flux monitoring a multilayer
fission chamber with 3.066+-0.006 mg/cm2 U235 was used.
Placed at 197.214 m from the neutron source, in front
The efficiency of detecting a fission event

x4freetext: - The measured efficiencies were corrected for the
extended volume and for the self-attenuation of the
gamma rays in the sample by means of MCNP code
- For the attenuation and multiple scattering of the
neutrons in the sample using MCNP simulations -
at 18 MeV it reaches ~50%. For other transitions <10%.
using Pb207(n,2n gamma) cross section from
Data values are extracted from the experiment labeled
as "EXP I" . Two experiments overlap very well.
"EXP I" is more complete and has better statistics.
The total uncertainty on the HPGe
efficiency was between 1.7% and 2.1% up to 1.4-MeV
gamma-ray energy, ~4.5% for the gamma energy > 1.4MeV.
The uncertainty of the activity of the 152Eu
The total inelastic and the level cross sections were
constructed using the angle integrated gamma production
cross sections and the evaluated level scheme of 206Pb.
using TALYS ver.1.6 for the sate of the art

The first level that decays directly to the ground
state and was not observed in the present experiment
is at 3744.3 keV. Above 3.762 MeV the data values
should be regarded as low limits of the inelastic
cross section. However, this limit is very close to
the precise value because most of the inelastic
strength is collected through the first gamma
transition, which is the most intense .
Above 3.7 MeV these values should be regarded as low
limits of the inelastic cross section.
